                <tr> <!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="title" --> 
                  <td align="left" class="maintitle"><strong>MA in Victorian Studies<br>
                    Postgraduate Diploma in Victorian Studies</strong></td>
                  <!-- InstanceEndEditable --></tr>
                <tr> 
                  <td align="left" class="bodytext">&nbsp; </td>
                </tr>
                <tr> <!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="main text" --> 
                  <td align="left" valign="top" class="bodytext"> <p>The MA in 
                      Victorian Studies offers postgraduate students a uniquely 
                      flexible, wide ranging and affordable opportunity to study 
                      the Victorian period. It is closely linked with the <a href="http://www.tasc.ac.uk/lcvs/">Leeds 
                      Centre for Victorian Studies</a> which is based at Leeds Trinity 
                      &amp; All Saints and involves other universities in the 
                      UK and beyond, in a programme of seminars, colloquia and 
                      conferences. The Centre is also the base for The Journal 
                      of Victorian Culture, which is published in conjunction 
                      with Edinburgh University Press.</p>
                    <p><strong>Course Content</strong><br>
                      <em>Core Modules</em><br>
                      The Victorians includes:<br>
                      &#8226; Politics and Society <br>
                      &#8226; Literature and Culture <br>
                      <br>
                      Approaches and Methods for Victorian Studies includes: <br>
                      &#8226; Sources and Methods for Research in Victorian Studies 
                      <br>
                      &#8226; Interpretation and Critical Practice in Victorian 
                      Studies <br>
                      <br>
                      <em>Option Modules </em><br>
                      A selection of the following are offered each year. Module 
                      subjects include: <br>
                      &#8226; The Changing Expectations of Victorian Women <br>
                      &#8226; Women and Art in Victorian Society<br>
                      &#8226; The Victorian Railway <br>
                      &#8226; The Novels of George Eliot <br>
                      &#8226; Victorian Identities: Gender and Sexual Morality 
                      in the Victorian Age <br>
                      &#8226; The Victorians and Religion <br>
                      &#8226; The Novels of the Bront&euml;s <br>
                      &#8226; Victorian Art and Architecture <br>
                      &#8226; Oscar Wilde <br>
                      &#8226; Victorian Science and Technology<br>
                      &#8226; Victorian Ethics<br>
                      &#8226; The Victorians and the Twentieth Century <br>
                      <br>
                      Dissertation or Report <br>
                      <br>
                      <strong>Assessment</strong> <br>
                      The first core module is assessed by a written examination 
                      at the end of the first semester. The remaining core module 
                      and all option modules are assessed by an essay/research 
                      essay, to be submitted at the end of the module. Finally, 
                      you will submit either a report or a dissertation, which 
                      consists of a piece of original research conducted on a 
                      subject of personal interest. <br>
                      <br>
                      <strong>Facilities and Resources </strong><br>
                      Our staff expertise in Victorian Studies covers a broad 
                      range. In addition to our new library and computer centre, 
                      you will have access to primary source material and extensive 
                      secondary literature on the Victorian period at the University 
                      of Leeds. <br>
                      <br>
                      <strong>Flexible Study</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                      <li> Full or part-time study: the MA is a modular degree 
                        designed to be taken at your own pace, between one and 
                        four years. </li>
                      <li> Evening sessions: held between 7-9pm so that study 
                        can be combined with full-time employment. </li>
                      <li> Flexible learning: the MA is designed to be tailored 
                        to your particular needs. It offers a mixture of taught 
                        and research modules where you undertake your own work 
                        under close personal supervision. </li>
                      <li> Wide range of subjects: after taking two broad-ranging 
                        compulsory core modules, you will have a wide range of 
                        option modules to choose from. </li>
                      <li> Chance to undertake supervised research: <br>
                        as part of your degree, you will undertake either a dissertation 
                        (14,000-18,000 words) or a research report (7,000-9,000 
                        words) on a subject of your choice. </li>
                      <li> Choice of MA or Postgraduate Diploma: study for a shorter 
                        period, taking fewer modules, and take the Postgraduate 
                        Diploma instead of the MA. </li>
                      <li>Pay as you learn: the cost of the MA is phased so you 
                        can pay module by module. Course fees are very competitive, 
                        about half the standard cost for most taught Masters degrees.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p> <strong>Entry Requirements</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                      <li> A good honours degree, either in a discipline relating 
                        to the broad area of Victorian Studies, or with some relevant 
                        content</li>
                      <li> Successful applicants will usually be offered a place 
                        on the basis of an application form, supporting letter, 
                        referees&#8217; reports and an interview</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p> <strong>Contact Details<br>
                      <br>
                      </strong>Course Director: Dr Jane de Gay<br>
                      For an informal discussion: 0113 283 7329<br>
                      Email: <a href="mailto:j.degay@leedstrinity.ac.uk">j.degay@leedstrinity.ac.uk</a> <br>
                      <br>
                      For more information: <br>
                      Telephone: 0113 283 7305<br>
                      Fax: 0113 283 7200<br>
                      Email: <a href="mailto:j.hamblin@leedstrinity.ac.uk">j.hamblin@leedstrinity.ac.uk</a> </p>
